<LENGTH>
<P>
152 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shame on Channel 5 for running horribly "colorized" versions of classic films 
marred by Turner Program Services. I tried watching "The Big Sleep" and it 
looked ludicrous, a true desecration of a piece of art. Black and white was 
absolutely essential to the mood. Do the Spanish slop colored paint on 
Picasso's "Guernica"? 
</P>
<P>
I turned down the color on my set, but found it too bright and in need of 
contrast adjusting. It still didn't look right. I've refused to watch 
colorization before, but I really wanted to see this movie. 
</P>
<P>
As for the advertisers, I saw their commercials in black and white. Their 
impact was greatly diminished. I would have seen them as you'd intended if KTLA 
had shown the film as its artists had intended. 
</P>
<P>
Thanks to Television Times for printing no checks in front of the film's title 
and noting (color) after it. I'll certainly avoid them in the future. 
</P>
<P>
Bruce Kuehn, North Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
