</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
120 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CURRENT PAPERBACKS: THE PIGEON BY PATRICK SUSKIND (WASHINGTON SQUARE PRESS: 
$5.95) 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SONJA BOLLE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Patrick Suskind's second novel focuses on 24 hours in the life of Jonathan 
Noel, an isolated, alienated Parisian bank guard who makes Camus' Mersault seem 
like a glad-hander. Noel's remote existence is so meticulously ordered that the 
unexpected appearance of an ordinary pigeon in the hallway of his rooming house 
plunges him into a crisis of despair and doubt. 
</P>
<P>
Like Job -- to whom he would probably compare himself -- Noel receives a rebuke 
from On High. A distant peal of thunder replaces the Voice Out of the 
Whirlwind, reminding him of his humanity and the need for companionship. 
Grotesque, funny and often moving, this brief book is warmer and more affirming 
than Suskind's celebrated first novel, "Perfume." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Book Review; Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072389-0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 85692 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 23, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Book Review; Page 15; Book Review Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1622 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENDPAPERS: 'SLEPT THROUGH ANY POETRY LATELY?' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JACK MILES, Times Book Editor 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Slept through any poetry lately?" The question is a headline in the July issue 
of "The Write Stuff," the newsletter of the Pomona Valley Writers' Assn. 
</P>
<P>
Poetry haters? On the contrary, poetry devotees of an indefatigable ardor, 
sleeping only as lovers sleep, with slaked passion. The PVWA is sponsoring a 
40-hour weekend workshop in the mountains near Green Valley Lake, an "endurance 
experience for poetry lovers," including "round-the-clock readings (for the 
mind); food, fresh air &amp; exercise (for the body); and an intimate, 
inspirational setting &amp; time to create (for the soul)." "Plan to 
participate/present/produce!" members are exhorted, but a warning follows: 
"Maximum occupancy -- 20 poets." 
</P>
<P>
I dream of being the Green Valley Lake hotelier whose job it is to enforce 
maximum occupancy against the 21st poet: "Sorry, ma'am, it's the fire code. 
Just doing my job." Far be it from me, however, to gainsay round-the-clock 
poetry reading for those tough enough to take it. If marathon therapy can break 
down neuroses, maybe marathon poetry reading can break down writer's block. 
</P>
<P>
Poetry therapy in the strict sense (if strict is the right word) is thriving in 
Southern California. Perhaps for kindred reasons, so is actors' poetry, or 
actors' poetry therapy. In my experience, actors are never happier than when 
they see the psychic agony of a fellow actor bleeding through into the 
performance. Cafe Largo, the actors' poetry night club, struck me on my one 
visit to it as a cross between equity waiver and psychiatric grand rounds. 
</P>
<P>
Still, what all these forms of nouvelle poesie have in common is important. 
They are all group experiences and as such a part of a multifaceted shift to 
performance in all of American arts and letters. And that shift is no joke: 
Henry M. Sayre's "The Object of Performance: The American Avant-Garde Since 
1970" (University of Chicago Press) claims that this shift defines the new 
avant-garde. In the visual arts, Sayre sees a move away from exhibition toward 
mixed-media performance. In poetry, the analogous move would be away from print 
to -- well, stick around: We're finding out. 
</P>
<P>
The two shifts have points of direct contact. Reviewer George Leonard writes 
(Book Review, July 16) of a pioneering performance, Yvonne Rainer's 1962 
"Ordinary Dance," which was "a collage of pure dance movements and observed 
behavior." "Instead of music, Rainer spoke 'an autobiographical narrative' as 
she danced. Her 'dance' was itself often a mimicking of everyday motions, even 
facial expressions, that she'd observed in the subway." Leonard muses: "Should 
we call that dance or mime? 'Dance-supported confessional prose poetry'? " 
</P>
<P>
How about cartoon? I ask, thinking of Jules Feiffer, who has been drawing 
something like dance-supported confessional prose poetry for 25 years -- 
laughing at it but, clearly, enormously and lastingly struck by it. Both the 
comedy and the pathos of Feiffer's dancer -- in her black leotard, with her 
swooping hair -- is that she is a woman. Imagine a man in all those cartoons, 
and the effect, simultaneously poignant and funny, evaporates. In this, Henry 
Sayre would find only confirmation since he maintains that the new performance 
art has been female in no small measure because women have been excluded from 
mainstream art galleries. 
</P>
<P>
Women are also notable by their relative absence from John Ashbery and David 
Lehman's confidently titled "Best Poems of 1988," reviewer Ian Gregson notes 
today on Page 3, in the first part of a six-part Summer Poetry Series, a series 
we hope to make an annual feature of the Book Review. Also missing from that 
volume, Gregson says, is another element that Sayre finds prominent in the new 
performance art; namely, politics or what Gregson calls simply realism. The 
poets that Ashbery selects wouldn't be likely to write about abortion, for 
example. By the same token, the mainstream New York galleries that Sayre 
surveys wouldn't be likely to exhibit paintings on abortion. So what do the 
women do? They put on their ballet slippers and vote with their feet: "A Dance 
to John Rehnquist." (Jules, are you taking notes?) 
</P>
<P>
At the popular level, in America's television culture, the shift to performance 
may have taken place a generation ago. But poetry and painting are among our 
oldest, most durable and most conservative forms. We should expect them to be 
among the last to be, as Marshall McLuhan put it, tribalized. 
</P>
<P>
In the long run, however, they may well tribalize -- or re-tribalize -- more 
easily than fiction, a younger but intrinsically more private form. Most 
fiction is, to begin with, simply too long to perform. Do I hear you cry 
"Nicholas Nickleby!"? A fair objection, but "Nicholas Nickleby" was a unique 
effort, scarcely the start of a movement. Poetry readings -- thousands of them, 
all year long, all over the country -- do constitute a movement. And the shift 
to more elaborately mounted "literary" performance carries the movement a step 
further. 
</P>
<P>
Hitherto, the great strength of fiction was that it contained its own set, 
lights, sound, special effects within itself. A play written with such 
completeness would foil its own performance: It would render actors, director, 
etc., superfluous. A lyric poem written at such length, given the demanding 
intensity of lyric language, would be murderous. Once the shift to performance 
begins, however, the relative incompleteness of lyric and drama become a more 
crucial strength than ever and, by the same token, the completeness of fiction 
becomes a weakness. 
</P>
<P>
Of Michael Palmer, winner of this year's PEN USA Center West poetry prize, 
critic Norman Finkelstein has written -- with admiration -- that he is "that 
rarity, a major poet who is almost totally unreadable." Totally unreadable? The 
compliment reads like an insult. But recall that many fine plays are 
essentially unreadable. We don't care because unreadable, spoken of a play, 
does not mean unperformable. If the play is any good, unreadable may mean 
simply incomplete in the right way. Palmer is incomplete in a poet's, not a 
playwright's, way, but his incompleteness nonetheless is compatible with 
performance in a way that would scarcely be true of any fiction. You can 
rewrite a novella or a short story for the stage. But, if you wanted, you could 
choreograph a Palmer poem as written. And the step from poetry that may be 
performed to poetry that must be performed -- poetry whose printed version is 
only a kind of prompt -- may be smaller than it seems. 
</P>
<P>
Novelists relish solitude and control. They write for readers like themselves, 
readers who rejoice in the compact package that provides all they need for a 
rich intellectual, emotional, deliciously private experience. If you are that 
kind of person, the shift to performance may strip your gears. But the 20 poets 
reading round the clock -- and apparently eating, jogging and generally 
rusticating together as well -- may not be quite like you. Neither may be the 
actors gathered of a night at Cafe Largo -- and otherwise not given to the 
sessions of sweet silent page-turning. (No insult here. See Page 3: Ashbery 
doesn't read either.) 
</P>
<P>
The promise of a shift to performance in painting and poetry is the promise of 
an infusion of energy and relevance. The threat in it is the threat that all 
artists will be busted to set-designer and all writers to scriptwriter. The 
situation is deeply ambiguous, so much so that if poetry is alive and well in 
Los Angeles, the performance capital of the world, we do right to wonder 
whether it is Los Angeles or poetry that has changed more. 
</P>
<P>
Over the last two years, as the Book Review has continued to publish a poem 
each week while cutting back on the number of poetry reviews, one distinguished 
poet who has written in support is Donald Hall, winner of the 1988 National 
Book Critics Circle poetry prize for "The One Day," a book-length poem that 
successfully defied excerpting in our little poetry box and may well have 
resisted public reading by its own author. No surprise here: Hall has publicly 
decried the spread of what he calls "McPoetry"; that is, light, brief, often 
wry poems written, consciously or unconsciously, with public reading in mind. 
Though he has, to be sure, written short poems that read beautifully and even a 
children's book, "The Ox-Cart Man," that reads beautifully again and again (the 
kid test), Hall is more aware than most of what can be lost by the shift to 
performance. 
</P>
<P>
And yet the gains may be real too. T. S. Eliot had a way of reading his own 
poetry that seemed to constrict his windpipe to about 12 picas' diameter. The 
result was, to push the metaphor, that you could hear every kern and serif. And 
too many poets, even now, seem to take Eliot as their public-speaking model. 
When you begin with a poem that, as to its content, reads like a philosophy 
lecture heard by a sleeping student (see Gregson, Page 3), the Eliot tradition 
of public reading may induce terminal narcolepsy. 
</P>
<P>
No one falls asleep at Cafe Largo, thank God for actors, and I venture to say 
that the PVWA 20 won't drowse away their 40 hours either. If we're lucky, the 
shift to performance will, by degrees, bring the vigor of song, chants ("We 
Will Ree Lee Rock-You!"), cheers, slang, slogans and related oral stimuli back 
into poetic play. If we're unlucky, however, the same shift may frustrate the 
long strenuous coupling that perhaps alone can bring a serious reader into 
intimacy and then identity with the mind of a great artist. That secret 
struggle, I confess, is more my own way, and I prize most those who prize (and 
preserve) it as a cultural habit. But we know, don't we, in what city and what 
century we find ourselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Jules Feiffer. By permission of Universal Press Syndicate. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
