<HEADLINE>
<P>
TIAN AN MEN SQUARE; 
</P>
<P>
IN THE TRADITIONAL VIEW IT IS CENTER OF BEIJING, CHINA AND THE UNIVERSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT M. POOLE, National Geographic 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For Chinese citizens, few places mean as much, in history or in symbol, as the 
Gate of Heavenly Peace (Tian An Men), the massive vermilion wall that guards 
the southern entrance to Beijing's Forbidden City. 
</P>
<P>
Hundreds and perhaps thousands of protesting students died in the shadow of the 
gate early in June, before the tanks and rifles of the 27th Army. It was no 
accident the youths chose Tian An Men Square, which lies before the gate, as 
their stage. 
</P>
<P>
Even before the creation of Communist China 40 years ago, Tian An Men was known 
as the place where government and the governed met. After the Ming emperors 
built their capital at Beijing in the early 15th Century, Tian An Men became 
the focus of the dynasty's most elaborate public ceremony, "The Gold Phoenix 
Issues an Edict," in which court officials announced imperial policy from a 
rostrum on the gate, long before written copies of the mandate were conveyed to 
the provinces. 
</P>
<P>
The emperor's benevolent power, subjects believed, flowed southward from the 
throne room, past the walled fortress of the Forbidden City, and through Tian 
An Men like a calming river that branched into the far reaches of his empire. 
</P>
<P>
When the People's Republic of China was founded Oct. 1, 1949, this was the 
place where Communist Party leader Mao Tse-tung raised the country's new flag. 
</P>
<P>
"In the traditional Chinese view, Tian An Men was not only the center of the 
capital, but the center of the country and the center of the universe," says 
Anthony J. Kane, director of the China Council of the Asia Foundation, a New 
York-based educational institution committed to the study and understanding of 
Asian culture. 
</P>
<P>
The gate remains a symbol of central authority. An image of the long, low 
building, with its sweeping roof upturned to fend off evil forces, is stamped 
on Chinese coins, currency, airline tickets, and policemen's badges. 
Schoolchildren learn to sing "I Love Tian An Men Square," much as others learn 
"America" or "La Marseillaise." 
</P>
<P>
Tian An Men Square is, at 98 acres, the largest city square in the world, a 
pancake-flat expanse of paving stones inspired by Moscow's Red Square. Tian An 
Men was created by the Communist government, which cleared away a rat's maze of 
gray houses, walls and alleys that used to squat outside the imperial compound. 
</P>
<P>
Thousands of tourists from the provinces flock to the square to see museums and 
monuments to the revolution and to have their pictures taken by vendors in 
front of the old gate. In normal times the atmosphere is easy, with vacationers 
gawking, licking flavored ice, and pointing at the sights, while staid Beijing 
residents drift to and from work on their black Flying Pigeon bicycles, 
accompanied by the festive tinkling of thousands upon thousands of bike bells. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Mao Still Haunts 
</P>
<P>
Although more than a decade has passed since Mao's death, the late chairman 
still haunts Tian An Men Square. At the plaza's south end, hundreds of the 
reverent and the curious line up daily, hats in hand, to visit the Chairman Mao 
Tse-tung Memorial Hall, a gray mausoleum built in the same heroic proportions 
as the emperor's quarters. Here the founder of modern China lies on view under 
glass. 
</P>
<P>
At Tian An Men Square's northern end, Mao's portrait peers down from Tian An 
Men Gate, where he liked to review thousands of marching Red Guards, the 
radical youths who held his little red poetry books aloft and greeted the Great 
Helmsman with a chant once reserved for emperors: "Ten thousand years! Ten 
thousand! Ten thousand and ten thousand!" 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
Site of Testing 
</P>
<P>
Along with the worshipful, Tian An Men has also drawn the disaffected from all 
parts of China. Traditionally, the capital gates have been a forum for testing 
the limits of political speech. 
</P>
<P>
Even before there was a China, a legendary king named Yao encouraged his 
subjects to carve their criticisms of government officials on wooden pillars 
outside his palace, so he would know of commoners' concerns. The wooden columns 
are gone now, but they are recalled by two pairs of white marble huabiao that 
support the gate at Tian An Men. 
</P>
<P>
Perhaps with that tradition in mind, Chinese gathered before the columns of 
Tian An Men to press the Qing emperor for reforms in government and education 
between 1895 and 1900. It was here the last dynasty collapsed in 1912 and here 
that guards shot and bayoneted 47 students to death in 1926, while the youths 
were protesting what they considered undue foreign influence in Chinese 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
Even Mao's Cultural Revolution, which began in Tian An Men, finally ended 
there. A million students poured into the capital to mourn the death of Premier 
Chou En-lai in 1976, and their mourning swiftly turned into a riot, aimed at 
the repressive Maoists then in power. Police brutally beat hundreds of the 
youths and made mass arrests, but the students eventually prevailed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Bicyclists skirt large puddle in front of Gate of Heavenly Peace at 
southern entrance to the Forbidden City. Below, a policeman directs traffic in 
Tian An Men Square, the largest city square in world, which attracts tourists, 
worshipers and the disaffected from all over China. National Geographic 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072389-0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 85711 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 23, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Part 1; Page 2; Column 4; National Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
130 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE NATION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tempers were hot and separate sets of roadblocks kept outsiders away from the 
St. Regis Indian Reservation in Upstate New York, where federal and state 
authorities had raided four gambling casinos earlier last week. About 50 state 
troopers sealed the area around the reservation, which straddles the Canadian 
border near Hogansburg, and Mohawk Indians closed the roads within the 
14,460-acre territory for a third day. "We're detouring traffic around the 
reservation because they've shut down the roads inside," said State Police Sgt. 
Michael Downs. Tribal chiefs, who have written to Gov. Mario M. Cuomo calling 
the dawn raid Thursday an "act of war," meanwhile agreed to hold a referendum 
this week on whether the reservation should continue to sponsor gambling 
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
POLICE RAIDS; GAMBLING -- NEW YORK (STATE); CASINOS; AMERICAN INDIANS -- NEW 
YORK (STATE); INDIAN RIGHTS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
