<HEADLINE>
<P>
FIXER-UPPER ART; 
</P>
<P>
WHY MANY CONTEMPORARY ARTWORKS ARE FALLING APART -- AND HOW CONSERVATORS ARE 
FIGHTING BACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUZANNE MUCHNIC 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Most visitors at "A Forest of Signs," at the Museum of Contemporary Art's 
Temporary Contemporary facility in Little Tokyo, see an intriguing array of 
ideas set forth in texts and objects. Art conservators see a mass of problems. 
</P>
<P>
Yellow blotches have appeared on the faces of poets, philosophers and painters 
in Mike Kelley's corridor of portraits, called "Pay for Your Pleasure." 
</P>
<P>
Some of Cindy Sherman's photographs are rippled, a few so badly that 
replacement prints had to be substituted for the ones originally sent to the 
show. 
</P>
<P>
Three vinyl panels in Gretchen Bender's "People and Pain," a neon-lighted work 
based on 1988 movie titles, came unglued and fell off during shipping. 
</P>
<P>
The paper on Mitchell Syrop's panels that borrow the advertising phrase, "lift 
and separate," have themselves begun to lift and separate from their backing. 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Koons' polychromed wood sculptures, less than a year old, were late in 
arriving because they needed repairs, registrar Mo Shannon said. 
</P>
<P>
What is the meaning of this? Is the art of our time falling apart? 
</P>
<P>
In some cases, yes, and the implications are serious for artists who want to be 
remembered, for collectors who pay ever-higher prices for contemporary art and 
for museums charged with maintaining the art. Furthermore, the problem isn't 
limited to artists' latest creations. Conservation problems plague the entire 
field of contemporary art (the contemporary art period generally is defined as 
1945 to the present). 
</P>
<P>
Some of Robert Rauschenberg's most prized "Combines" from the '50s, for 
example, are in need of serious attention. "Untitled (Man in the White Shoes)," 
a 1955 Rauschenberg in MOCA's Panza collection, is undergoing an $18,000 
conservation job ($11,000 of it paid for by a grant from the National Endowment 
for the Arts). 
</P>
<P>
The 7-foot-tall box-like construction, containing a stuffed chicken, gauze 
curtains, a pair of men's shoes, an anonymous landscape painting and 
autobiographical collaged elements (childhood drawings by Rauschenberg's son, 
Christopher, and photographs of his family), requires a variety of conservation 
skills. 
</P>
<P>
MOCA has no staff conservator, so the museum has contracted four specialists to 
do the work: Tatyana Thompson for the painted parts of the piece, Glenn Wharton 
for the objects, Mark Watters for paper components and Sharon Shore for 
textiles. Shore has already completed the job of cleaning the chicken, which is 
now wrapped in plastic until the rest of the conservation is done. 
</P>
<P>
Specialists trace contemporary art's conservation ills to the flowering of an 
experimental approach to materials and techniques. "Before World War II, 
artists' materials were limited. They painted on panel or canvas and there was 
a limited number of sculpture materials. But since then, everything has become 
fair game -- anything out of the garbage dump or the refrigerator," said Pieter 
Meyers, head of conservation at the County Museum of Art. 
</P>
<P>
Along with this liberated approach to the physical components of art came a 
change of attitude. "In the '50s, Action Painting was de rigueur. If you spent 
more than 30 seconds on anything you were overworking it," said artist George 
Herms, describing some of his early works that were held together by a single 
nail. His vintage assemblages of castoff materials were made to look old and 
tattered. 
</P>
<P>
Disdain for workmanship was a result of "growing up with the atomic bomb," 
Herms said. "The generation of artists who came to maturity knowing that we 
could be blown up any minute didn't see much point in making art to last 
forever." 
</P>
<P>
Whether creating from a new sense of freedom or as a political statement, 
artists in the last three decades have produced a proliferation of notably 
impermanent art. And now that conservators must deal with these works, there is 
no shortage of horror stories. 
</P>
<P>
One well known case concerns five murals commissioned in 1961 for Harvard 
University from Abstract Expressionist Mark Rothko. Because of unstable 
pigments and overexposure to sunlight, the paintings began to fade almost as 
soon as they were installed in the Holly Oak Center, a lounge for faculty and 
administrators. Deterioration continued until first one panel and then the 
whole set had to be removed. 
</P>
<P>
"There's no expectation that these paintings will ever return to exhibition or 
to permanent installation," said Richard Koshalek, director of the Museum of 
Contemporary Art, who presented the Rothko case last winter at a conservation 
symposium in Los Angeles. The loss of "a major set of post-World War II 
paintings" (one that would be worth millions on today's market) is particularly 
bitter because it occurred at one of the nation's most distinguished 
institutions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Rothko is partly responsible for the Harvard disaster. He sometimes bought his 
paints at Woolworth's and used egg whites for a medium and for surface effects. 
But he wasn't alone in his cavalier use of materials. Hard pressed for cash, 
fellow Abstract Expressionists Jackson Pollock and Franz Kline often used 
inexpensive house paint, which tends to shrink, crack and discolor on canvas. 
Kline mixed thick paints that had different drying properties and used 
incorrect proportions of medium and paint. 
</P>
<P>
A subsequent generation of Color Field and stain paintings on unprimed canvas 
has faded, sometimes changing color to an extraordinary degree, and exposed 
fabric has yellowed and become dirty, according to Joseph Fronek, conservator 
of paintings at the County Museum of Art. At work on "Cinema di Pepsi V," a 
1966 painting by Frank Stella, Fronek explained that contemporary unvarnished 
works have to be dry-cleaned with erasers or special solvents that don't wet 
the fabric and cause it to expand or contract. Old Master canvases, on the 
other hand, are covered with paint and sealed with varnish so they can be 
cleaned with small amounts of water or organic solvents. 
</P>
<P>
Problems can be even more severe when artists such as Pop master Claes 
Oldenburg venture into highly unorthodox materials. Insects have attacked his 
chocolate sculptures, and his fragile chicken-wire and plaster objects from the 
early '60s are dirty and cracked, including those in MOCA's collection. 
Oldenburg's "Giant Pool Balls," in the County Museum of Art's collection, has 
been repainted twice -- most recently by a body shop that specializes in 
painting luxury autos. 
</P>
<P>
Such examples indicate a legacy of deteriorating art. It's a fact of life for 
artists who favor unconventional materials and pride themselves on challenging 
traditional notions about permanence and value. It's also a fact of life for 
collectors who pay private conservators $50 to $100 an hour for their services. 
</P>
<P>
But should contemporary art be allowed to rot in peace? Or is a massive 
education campaign needed to awaken artists and collectors to a threat to our 
cultural heritage? A series of interviews with artists, conservators and 
collectors produced the following responses to these queries: 
</P>
<P>
 -- Is the conservation of contemporary art a serious issue? 
</P>
<P>
Conservators who breathe new life into damaged art and serious-minded 
collectors agree that it is, but artists' opinions vary. "It's not a huge 
concern for me. I'm more interested in spurring ideas," said Mike Kelley, whose 
past exhibitions include entire walls of raw, unframed drawings. "When I was 
young, I just used anything I had access to. Now I try to use paper that won't 
discolor, but ephemeral material is part of the anti-heroicism of my work." 
</P>
<P>
The banner-like portraits in "A Forest of Signs" were done to his 
specifications by a house painter, Kelley said, and the yellowed portions are 
the result of too much thinner mixed with the pigment. At first Kelley was 
shocked by the discoloration, which occurred almost immediately, he said, "but 
now it doesn't bother me. It gives a sense of age that's appropriate to the 
subject." 
</P>
<P>
"I think that all viewers should get the same ride," Herms said, explaining 
that he wants today's audience to have the same experience of his vintage 
pieces as people who saw them many years ago. The letters LOVE that appear on 
his works are "a seal of approval," he said, and an indication that he wants 
viewers 100 years from now to see the work as he created it. 
</P>
<P>
Bruce Houston, who is best known for fragile assemblages made of tiny plastic 
toys, has taken to enclosing some of his works in plexiglass boxes to avoid 
breakage, though he believes that interferes with their sculptural quality. He 
also worries about the durability of the plastic components. "Plastic cups on 
the beach seem to last forever, but we don't really know how durable some of 
these plastics are," he said. 
</P>
<P>
"An artist has to weigh choices -- the effect of the moment against 
permanence," said Alexis Smith, whose narrative collages are based on American 
Pop culture and literature. That balance tends to change as an artist matures, 
she said. "At the beginning when you are giving your work away, you don't feel 
a big responsibility for making it last. But when people start paying 
reasonable prices for it, you take more care so that you and they won't have 
problems. I try to make things as well as I can, as archival as possible. I 
don't skimp on materials or technology." 
</P>
<P>
 -- When is conservation appropriate and how far should artists and 
conservators go to repair damage? 
</P>
<P>
"As soon as an artwork enters our collection, we have a big commitment to do 
whatever we can to maintain the original intent of the artist," Meyers said. 
That philosophy may indicate treatment, but "it also prevents us from doing all 
kinds of things," he said. 
</P>
<P>
It may even prevent the museum from calling in the artist, as it did last year 
when conservators found a flaw on the surface of "Blue Curve III," a 1972 
diamond-shaped painting. Meyers said: "Ellsworth Kelly loves to have perfect 
surfaces. Even a thumbprint is an imperfection to him. He was very helpful and 
repainted the piece. But now I have difficulty with it (Kelly's repair). How do 
I know it is the same color blue, that the surface is exactly the same, that 
there are not subtle differences? I would not do that again. I would leave it 
the way it was, the way he intended it because Ellsworth Kelly in 1988 not the 
same as Ellsworth Kelly in 1972." 
</P>
<P>
"When I am called in to restore a work, I try to put myself in the spirit of 
the artist who made the piece 30 years ago, but I usually break more than I 
repair," Herms said. "I call it restoration comedy." 
</P>
<P>
The crew working at MOCA on Rauschenberg's "Combine" has no intention of 
putting the piece in pristine condition. Their cleaning and repairs will be 
"consistent with the artist's presumed intention," according to a prepared 
statement. Self-destruction is often built into contemporary art in the form of 
incompatible materials, said Wharton, a member of the MOCA team. The best that 
conservators can do in such cases is "to help the art live a little longer," he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
The rule of thumb for conservation is that all treatments should be reversible 
and that the artist's intentions at the time of creation should be honored. 
Conservators say that the best thing a museum can provide is a stabile 
environment, one in which temperature and humidity are constant. "We can't stop 
deterioration, but we can retard it because we have an ideal environment. The 
problem is more difficult for smaller institutions and private collectors," 
Meyers said. 
</P>
<P>
 -- Are experimental methods and materials the only source of conservation 
problems? 
</P>
<P>
Absolutely not. 
</P>
<P>
A lack of knowledge about -- or concern for -- safe display and storage is a 
major cause of damage to contemporary art, conservators agree. 
</P>
<P>
"There's almost a total absence of knowledge on how to treat, preserve and 
store works of art" on the part of both individual and corporate collectors, 
Meyers said. "Most banks and other corporations that collect art have no 
conservators and don't know how to store art." 
</P>
<P>
Interior design also conflicts with conservation, according to Meyers. "The 
airy, light styles of today's houses are disastrous for contemporary art," 
which often contains unstable dies that fade easily in sunlight, he said. 
</P>
<P>
"Poor packing and shipping is a big killer of artworks," Smith said, citing 
another frequent complaint. 
</P>
<P>
Exhibitions, particularly those that travel from place to place, take a big 
toll on artworks. There's a limit to how many times, say, Frank Stella's 
painted metal constructions can be dismantled and reassembled without weakening 
them. When that sort of wear is combined with faulty packing and handling, the 
results can be disastrous. 
</P>
<P>
Collector Robert H. Halff, who often loans art to exhibitions, said that it is 
not unusual for loaned works to be damaged and that the problem is more likely 
to come from shipping and handling than the artist's workmanship. Known as a 
generous donor and lender, he said that some works in his collection are now 
too fragile to travel. 
</P>
<P>
Loans -- and even damage -- can produce good stories, however. One of Halff's 
past loans had a funny twist that he likes to tell visitors to his collection. 
An insect was stuck in the wax surface of his prized Jasper Johns' encaustic, 
"Figure 7," when Halff took it to Art Services to be specially framed for 
Johns' retrospective. Assuming the bug to be an intruder, Halff asked Manny 
Silverman of Art Services to remove it, but Silverman (who now has his own 
gallery) thought Johns might have put the insect in the art and intended it to 
stay. 
</P>
<P>
Halff contacted Johns, who said no, encaustic attracts bugs, so Silverman 
removed the visitor. But when Halff got the piece back from the exhibition a 
tiny piece of encaustic had chipped off exactly where the insect had been. "I 
call it 'Memorial to the Bug,' " Halff said. 
</P>
<P>
 -- What's the solution to the conservation of contemporary art? 
</P>
<P>
There's no quick fix, but a heightened awareness could lead to prevention of 
some of the most serious problems, conservators say. 
</P>
<P>
One hopeful sign is that conservators are building up experience in working 
with unorthodox materials. LACMA conservator Sharon Blank, for example, is a 
biochemist whose expertise in plastics has been in demand on everything from 
Barbie dolls and Tupperware to sculpture by Russian modernist Naum Gabo. At 
LACMA, she has worked on an Edward Kienholz assemblage and Charles Frazier's 
"Anno Domini 1962," a globe covered with plastic toys. 
</P>
<P>
Some conservators suggest that art schools might do more to educate their 
students about conservation, but artists often disagree. "There's a danger of 
making the work too precious before that's appropriate," Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
"When I teach at UCLA, we destroy everything at the end of the quarter," Herms 
said. 
</P>
<P>
"An artist should have an awareness of using proper materials, what paints are 
stabile, what technology to use. But there's no way to limit materials, to have 
a conservator's stamp of approval," Meyers said. 
</P>
<P>
While it's his business to be concerned about conservation, Meyers maintains a 
philosophical distance. "If we can't take out imperfections without changing 
the art, we have to change the way the public looks at art. Remember that we 
are not seeing Rembrandt's paintings the way Rembrandt painted them, but we 
still enjoy and appreciate them. The greens in Dutch 17th-Century paintings 
have turned brown, but our eyes have adjusted. It should be just as easy to 
adjust to changes in contemporary art." 
</P>
<P>
Herms injected a bit of humor into an otherwise worrisome situation: "I think 
we need cryogenics for art. The solutions to these problems will be discovered. 
In the meantime we should freeze the art." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Sharon Blank of LACMA with Charles Frazier's plastic-toy-covered globe. 
; Photo, Joseph Fronek of LACMA at work on "Cinema di Pepsi V," a 1966 painting 
by Frank Stella. He is using an eraser to remove marks and dirt from the 
canvas. GARY FRIEDMAN / L.A. Times; Photo, Mo Shannon of MOCA's Temporary 
Contemporary with "Untitled (Man in the White Shoes)," a 1955 work by Robert 
Rauschenberg that is undergoing an $18,000 conservation. TODD ANDERSON / L.A. 
Times; Photo, Sharon Blank, Joseph Fronek and Pieter Meyers, right, of LACMA 
examine an artwork. GARY FRIEDMAN / L.A. Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
