</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MOTION PICTURE INDUSTRY -- UNITED STATES; MOTION PICTURES; VIOLENCE 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA072389-0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 85953 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
July 23, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 46; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
1144 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
UNDER TWO DIFFERENT SHADOWS OF THE APOCALYPSE; 
</P>
<P>
COMPARING 'NEBRASKA,' 'WALK IN THE WOODS' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SYLVIE DRAKE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
There is a scene somewhere around the middle of Keith Reddin's "Nebraska" in 
which not one word is spoken. 
</P>
<P>
It happens when two military officers -- Swift and Fielding -- are on 24-hour 
duty in the hermetic launch center of a nuclear missile silo 70 feet 
underground. 
</P>
<P>
The lights go up. The men stare into space. Awkward minutes go by. Blackout. 
</P>
<P>
The scene speaks volumes. 
</P>
<P>
We've seen these guys there before. Alone together. Bored. Whiling away the 
suffocating tedium. We've also seen them earlier, in jest, rehearse the 
commands they'd have to execute to "enable" a successful launch. We know -- as 
they know -- that we're really talking about the possibility of nuclear 
annihilation. 
</P>
<P>
"Up there, who knows what's exactly going down," Fielding had said grandly over 
drinks one night to a bug-eyed army clerk he wanted to impress. "You gotta 
figure the worst." 
</P>
<P>
"Everything could be dust by now," echoed his buddy Swift, playing along. But 
something of that flippant bar-room banter lingered. One day on that stupefying 
duty in the pit, Swift asks Fielding, "Could you shoot me?" 
</P>
<P>
"Right now?" 
</P>
<P>
"Say I balk." 
</P>
<P>
"You wouldn't." 
</P>
<P>
"Say I do." 
</P>
<P>
"Come on." Fielding is incredulous. Swift insists. "I get cold feet, you gonna 
train the metal on me?" 
</P>
<P>
"Of course. And you would do the same." Would he? Some exchanges later the 
conversation is dropped. But the harm's been done. 
</P>
<P>
At the La Jolla Playhouse, where "Nebraska's" playing, we discover by degrees 
that no one on this forlorn base in the middle of nowhere is entirely rational. 
This business of baby-sitting rockets with the ability to pulverize 
civilization is not exactly life-enhancing. It provokes derangements. 
</P>
<P>
Swift, who entered the service because his father before him had proudly served 
as a career military officer, comes hard and slowly to the realization that 
this choice of profession may leave something to be desired, especially now 
that it has been nuclearly redefined. But not before he's done some things that 
don't add up -- such as asking Fielding the $64 question that puts his very 
fitness for the job on the line -- and straying from a rocky marriage (with the 
wife of his commanding officer, no less), a marriage he claims he wants to 
save. 
</P>
<P>
Nor is he the only person on base with performance problems. Gurney, the CO, is 
so tied up in knots he can't even complete a sentence. Any sentence. 
</P>
<P>
No wonder his wife takes courses at the local college, visits bars and has 
affairs as recreational therapy. They are warning flares to a husband as 
inarticulate sexually as he is verbally. 
</P>
<P>
Reddin doesn't have to fill in the blanks. They speak to us loud and clear. By 
the time that wordless scene in the middle of the play comes around, we know 
exactly what is not being said. 
</P>
<P>
All of this strange behavior is not strictly the effect of living in the shadow 
of the Apocalypse. Like Lee Blessing's "A Walk in the Woods" (seen two years 
ago at La Jolla), Reddin's "Nebraska" is not directly concerned with nuclear 
deterrence (as is "Woods") but with the deadlier terms of a life lived in the 
negative mode. Dedication to making sure something doesn't happen, instead of 
making things happen, is a killer. It's "living" spelled backwards. 
</P>
<P>
Blessing's "Walk," a discourse for two voices, is much more forward-looking. 
This zestful series of private conversations between an American arms 
negotiator and his Soviet counterpart as they roam the woods outside Geneva is 
engaging, personal, surprising, amusing and garrulous. They discuss everything 
-- from Mickey Mouse and banjos and brown suits and the likelihood of 
friendship to country Western music and -- oh yes, alternatives to the arms 
race. Even its outdoor setting is life-embracing. It does get around to testing 
some knotty questions, but it is, in a phrase, all happy talk. 
</P>
<P>
"Nebraska," on the other hand, is all strained silences. Its messages are found 
between, not in the lines. 
</P>
<P>
This is particularly unusual when you consider the origins of the piece. Reddin 
had been asked to develop a documentary for PBS on nuclear weapons systems. It 
never materialized but the playwright was left with stacks of research material 
and "became interested in looking at the subject from a smaller angle." 
Documentaries are anathema to plays, but "Nebraska" director Les Waters' 
description of the final product as "Strindberg Meets Pacman" fits. Aside from 
a mutual reliance on humor, what links the plays is contrast -- the degree to 
which they demonstrate that you can achieve similar ends through diametrically 
opposite means. 
</P>
<P>
The loquacious "Woods" sparkles with accessible wit. It thrives on verbal left 
turns as well as the difference between the fledgling American, naively 
convinced that his diplomacy can make a difference, and the world-weary Soviet, 
droll and down-to-earth, who knows that political systems shift without really 
changing. (This argument may have lost some of its bite now that glasnost is 
pointing another way.) 
</P>
<P>
"Nebraska" is more chilling. Its fundamental proposition has a negative thrust 
-- and we're not talking missiles -- that ultimately implodes. It's attrition 
vs. nutrition. The ravages of such an existence are subtle. They do their worst 
almost imperceptibly. But it doesn't take a savant or even a psychologist to 
tell us that a perpetual death watch is murder on the elan vital. A skillful 
playwright will do. 
</P>
<P>
That is where "Nebraska" shines -- not so much as it unfolds scene after 
taciturn scene, in an understated episodic build, but in the power of its 
cumulative effect. Unlike the lip-smacking "Woods," which declares its 
intentions early and tackles them head on, "Nebraska" is all implication and 
sour aftertaste. 
</P>
<P>
"Woods" comes sugarcoated. It is, therefore, much more of a crowd pleaser. Also 
a dream exercise for two actors. So it comes as no surprise that it was 
embraced for airing over PBS or that Des McAnuff, the artistic director at La 
Jolla who staged the original "Woods" (at the Yale Repertory, in La Jolla and 
in New York), has decided to mount two more versions of the piece next fall: In 
Moscow, with a pair of Soviet actors -- and in Vilnius, with a pair of 
Lithuanians. A perfect choice when you consider the play's portability, its 
dual nationality and topical appeal. 
</P>
<P>
It's unlikely that something as subtle and semaphoric as "Nebraska" would work 
particularly well on television which, as a medium, favors bolder and more 
declarative statements. And it's even less likely that it will find ready 
commercial markets. But a performance in the USSR or Lithuania would be an 
interesting idea -- in rep, perhaps, with "A Walk in the Woods"? 
</P>
<P>
Who is to say, on balance, if the play that says the least speaks the loudest? 
Or the other way around? There's virtue in both. What remains fascinating is 
the infinite variety of approaches to a subject. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Adam Colman Howard, left, as Fielding and Rob Knepper as Swift in Keith 
Reddin's "Nebraska." MICHA LANGER; Photo, Michael Constantine, left, and 
Lawrence Pressman in "A Walk in the Woods." L.A. Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
